x4freetext: Pelletron accelerator facility, New
Delhi
self-supporting 238U target of thickness 15 mg/cm**2
The gamma rays emitted by the fission fragments were
detected using the Indian National Gamma Array (INGA)
comprised of 18 Compton suppressed Clover detectors,
each having an intrinsic photopeak efficiency ~ 0.2%.
The clover detectors were mounted at a distance of 24
cm from the target with the accompanying anti-Compton
shields. These detectors were arranged in five rings
viz., 32 deg, 57 deg, 90 deg , 123 deg, and 148 deg
with respect to the beam direction and each detector
subtends an opening angle of 29 deg at the target
center. The Compton suppressed data were collected in
an event-by-event mode with the minimum requirement of
threefold prompt gamma -ray coincidence, for which the
event rate was 1.6 K/s with the beam current ~ 3 pnA.
The coincidence time gate for recording the data was
set at about 350 ns. The overall energy resolution in
the total projection spectrum of the gamma rays was
found to be about 1.8 keV at gamma ray energy 200 keV.
Fission fragment mass distribution
has been determined from the on-line measurement of
individual even-even fragment yields by analyzing the
gamma -gamma matrix. In the present work, the
independent yield of a particular fragment nucleus has
been determined from the coincidence of gamma rays of
2+ to 0+ and 4+ to 2+ transitions
18-O beam of energy 100 MeV
In the data analysis, a total of ~ 1.9 x 10**8
threefold
events have been considered and the gamma - gamma
matrix is constructed from the prompt gamma -ray
coincidence data. The data were analyzed using RADWARE
software to obtain the independent yields of the
fission fragments.
For some of the nuclei, the gamma rays of 2+ to 0+
and 4+ to 2+ transitions are very close in energy and
in such cases their relative yield was determined by
gating on higher transitions.
